summary:
The text provides a comprehensive overview of the Robot Operating System (ROS), a flexible and scalable framework for creating robot software. It is designed to be lightweight and easily integrated with other software frameworks. It is language-independent, meaning it can be implemented in any modern programming language, although Python, C++, and Lisp are the most commonly used. 

The ROS runtime "graph" is a peer-to-peer network of processes that are loosely coupled using the ROS communication infrastructure. The fundamental concepts of the ROS implementation are nodes, messages, topics, and services. Nodes are software processes that perform computation and represent a software module or component. They are uniquely identified by their name and have a node type, equivalent to their class in object-oriented programming. Nodes communicate with each other by passing messages, which are strictly typed data structures. 

The data exchange between nodes in ROS follows a publisher/subscriber pattern, with a node sending out a message by publishing it to a topic. A topic is a name that identifies a particular message flow, and a node can subscribe to a topic to receive this message. Topics are typed by the ROS message type, and communication only occurs if both the publisher and the subscriber of the topic are using the exact same message type. For unidirectional, streaming communication, nodes use topics. For remote procedure calls where a response to a request is needed, nodes use services.

The communication system in ROS is based on nodes, which are the basic units of computation, communicating with each other by passing messages. These messages are strictly typed data structures that can be composed of standard primitive types, arrays of primitive types, constants, and other messages. The messages are defined in message files, which specify the data structure of the message. ROS automatically generates source code to use these messages in a ROS node, in both C++ and Python.

The data exchange between nodes in ROS follows a publisher/subscriber pattern. A node sends out a message by publishing it to a topic, which is a name that identifies the message flow. A node can subscribe to a topic to receive this message. There can be multiple concurrent publishers and subscribers for a single topic, and a single node may publish and/or subscribe to multiple topics. The communication only occurs if both the publisher and the subscriber of the topic are using the exact same message type. The topics in ROS can be transmitted using TCP-IP and UDP.

Services are used for request/reply interactions. A node offers a service under a name and a client uses the service by sending the request message and awaiting the reply. Services are defined in service files, which are compiled to automatically generate a stub implementation of the service. The Master provides name registration and enables individual ROS nodes to locate one another. The Parameter Server is a shared, multi-variate dictionary that is accessible via network APIs and is used to store and retrieve parameters at runtime. Bags is a format for saving and playing back ROS messages.

The text also discusses various libraries and tools available in ROS. The tf library is used to represent transformations between coordinate frames over time. This library allows users to transform points, vectors, etc., between any two coordinate frames at any desired point in time. It is designed to provide a standard way to keep track of coordinate frames and transform data within an entire system. 

RVIZ, the 3D visualization tool in ROS, supports a variety of data types and allows users to select the appropriate configuration for each specific robot. Users can also customize the RVIZ interface by developing application-specific plugins. Other useful libraries that integrate with ROS include the Gazebo simulator, a 3D indoor and outdoor multi-robot simulator with dynamic and kinematic physics.

The Point Cloud Library (PCL) is a perception library focused on the manipulation and processing of three-dimensional data and depth images. OpenCV, the premier computer vision library, is also integrated with ROS, providing many common computer vision algorithms and utilities. Lastly, MoveIt!, a motion planning library that offers efficient implementations of state-of-the-art planning algorithms, can be used with any ROS-supported robot and planning data can be visualized with rviz and rqt plugins.

The text provides an in-depth exploration of the NumPy library in Python, a programming language. NumPy, short for 'Numerical Python', is a library that supports large, multi-dimensional arrays and matrices, and includes a vast collection of high-level mathematical functions to operate on these arrays. It is a crucial tool for numerical computations and is often used in conjunction with other packages like SciPy and Matplotlib as an alternative to MatLab, a widely used platform for technical computing.

The first section of the text delves into the process of defining structured data types in NumPy. The author provides examples of how to create an array with a single integer field 'age', and another array with three fields - 'name' (a string), 'age' (an integer), and 'marks' (a float). The author also provides a list of character codes that uniquely identify each built-in data type in NumPy, such as 'b' for boolean, 'i' for signed integer, 'f' for floating-point, and so on.

The second section of the text discusses various array attributes of NumPy. The author explains how to use the 'shape' attribute to get the dimensions of an array and how to resize an array. The 'ndim' attribute is used to get the number of array dimensions. The 'itemsize' attribute returns the length of each element of the array in bytes. The 'flags' attribute returns the current values of various properties of the array, such as whether the data is in a single contiguous segment, whether the array owns the memory it uses, whether the data area can be written to, and so on.

The final section of the text explains how to create a new ndarray object using the 'empty' function, which creates an uninitialized array of a specified shape and data type. The author also provides an example of how to use this function.

The text also provides an overview of the history of NumPy, which was developed by Jim Hugunin and later improved by Travis Oliphant in 2005, who incorporated features of another package, Numarray, into NumPy. The text also explains how to install and enable NumPy, which does not come with the standard Python distribution and must be installed separately. This can be done using pip, a popular Python package installer, or by using an installable binary package specific to the user's operating system.

The text introduces the ndarray object, the most important object defined in NumPy. An ndarray, or N-dimensional array, is a collection of items of the same type that can be accessed using a zero-based index. Each item in an ndarray takes the same size of block in the memory and is an object of data-type object (dtype). The ndarray can be created using an array function in NumPy, and any item extracted from an ndarray object is represented by a Python object of one of the array scalar types.

The text appears to be a table of contents or an index from a book or manual about NumPy. It lists a series of functions for manipulating arrays, including hstack, vstack, split, hsplit, vsplit, resize, append, insert, delete, and unique. It also discusses binary operators, string functions, mathematical functions, and arithmetic operations in NumPy. The final part of the text covers statistical functions and sort, search, and counting functions in NumPy. These functions allow for the calculation of minimum and maximum values, range, percentiles, median, mean, average, standard deviation, and variance of numeric data in arrays. The sort, search, and counting functions section likely covers functions for sorting arrays, searching for elements in arrays, and counting occurrences of elements in arrays.

The text provides a comprehensive guide on how to use NumPy, a Python library for working with arrays. It begins by discussing the use of numpy.dtype object in Python programming, explaining that a sequence of tuples can be used to define the type of data in each column of an array. The dtype can be set to None, allowing the type of the columns to be determined from the data itself, although this method is slower than setting the dtype explicitly. The dtype has as many fields as items in the sequence, and the field names are defined with the names keyword. The type of each column is determined iteratively from its data, starting with checking whether a string can be converted to a boolean, then to an integer, then to a float, then to a complex, and eventually to a string.

The text then delves into the use of the names argument, explaining that when dealing with tabular data, it is common to allocate a name to each column. This can be done using an explicit structured dtype or by using the names keyword with a sequence of strings or a comma-separated string. The names can also be defined from the data itself by using the names keyword with a value of True. The names will then be read from the first line, even if the line is commented out. If any other value is given to the names keyword, the new names will overwrite the field names defined with the dtype.

The text also discusses the use of the defaultfmt argument and the validation of names. If names=None but a structured dtype is expected, names are defined with the standard NumPy default of "f%i", yielding names like f0, f1, and so forth. This default can be overwritten with the defaultfmt argument, which takes any format string. The text also explains that field names should not contain any space or invalid character, or correspond to the name of a standard attribute, which would confuse the interpreter. The text concludes by mentioning the converters argument, which is used to define how the sequence of strings must be converted.

The text then discusses the use of the array of npy_intp variables, PyArray_STRIDES (obj), which shows how many bytes must be added to the current element pointer to get to the next element in each dimension. It also mentions the use of PyArray_GETPTR{k} (obj, . . . ) macros for arrays less than 4-dimensions. The text further explains the striding patterns of C-style contiguous arrays and Fortran-style contiguous arrays, and how to test whether the striding pattern of a particular array matches these styles.

The text provides an example of how to write a wrapper that accepts two input arguments and an output argument. The function returns None and updates the output array. The example includes a code snippet that demonstrates how to use the WRITEBACKIFCOPY semantics for NumPy v1.14 and above. The code makes use of arguments and includes error handling.

The text then discusses the use of Python as a "glue" language, particularly in the field of science. It explains how Python was initially used to connect large application codes running on supercomputers, and how this led to the development of Numeric, an array-like object that could be used to pass data between these applications. As Numeric developed into NumPy, more code could be written directly in NumPy. However, there are still times when there is a need to access compiled code, and the text concludes by stating that there are many resources available for learning to call other compiled libraries from Python.

The text is also a tutorial on how to use NumPy, starting with how to access elements in an array using indexing. It provides an example of creating an array using the arange function and reshaping it into a 3x5 matrix. The tutorial also explains how to check the shape, dimension, data type, item size, and type of the array.

The tutorial then moves on to array creation. It explains that arrays can be created from a regular Python list or tuple using the array function. The type of the resulting array is deduced from the type of the elements in the sequences. It also warns against a common error of calling the array function with multiple numeric arguments, rather than providing a single list of numbers as an argument. The tutorial also explains how to create arrays with initial placeholder content using the zeros, ones, and empty functions.

The tutorial then explains how to create sequences of numbers using the arange function, which returns arrays instead of lists. It also introduces the linspace function, which is used when it is not possible to predict the number of elements obtained due to finite floating point precision. The tutorial also explains how to print arrays, with one-dimensional arrays printed as rows, two-dimensional arrays as matrices, and three-dimensional arrays as lists of matrices. It also explains how to change the printing options to print the entire array.

The passage provides an in-depth tutorial on how to use the pivot_table function in the pandas library in Python. The pivot_table function is a tool used to create a spreadsheet-style pivot table as a DataFrame. The tutorial provides examples of how to use the function with different parameters and options. 

The first part of the tutorial demonstrates how to use the pivot_table function to create a pivot table with the index as 'Position' and the columns as 'City'. The values in the table are 'Age' and the aggfunc parameter is used to specify the aggregate function to be used on the values. The tutorial provides examples of how to use different aggregate functions such as sum and first. It also shows how to handle non-numeric data by using the 'first', 'last', 'sum', and 'join' aggregate functions.

The second part of the tutorial demonstrates how to use multiple columns in the index, columns, and values parameters. It also shows how to apply multiple aggregate functions in a single pivot table. The tutorial then shows how to add a new column to the DataFrame and how to apply specific functions to specific columns. The tutorial concludes with an example of how to use the stack and unstack functions to reshape the DataFrame.

The passage also provides a detailed explanation of various operations that can be performed on data using Python's pandas library. It begins by demonstrating how to create a new column in a dataframe by using the zip function to combine two lists and then applying a mathematical operation to each pair of elements. It then shows how to add a new column to a dataframe and calculate its mean, and how to add multiple columns to a dataframe by squaring the values in the existing columns. 

The tutorial then moves on to demonstrate how to add multiple columns to a dataframe on the fly by performing operations on existing columns. It also shows how to locate and replace data in a column, in this case, encoding 'male' as 0 and 'female' as 1. The tutorial then explains how to add a new row to a dataframe, and how to delete or drop rows from a dataframe using various methods, including the drop method and negative selection method.

The passage concludes by explaining how to reorder columns in a dataframe, and how to manipulate strings in a dataframe using regular expressions and slicing. It provides examples of how to extract strings with a specific regex, replace strings within a regex, and slice strings to get specific characters or substrings. It also explains how pandas handles slices and indices that are outside the range, returning NaN for indices and an empty string for slices.

The passage also provides a table of contents for a book about pandas, a software library written for the Python programming language for data manipulation and analysis. The book is divided into 23 chapters, each focusing on a different aspect of the pandas library. The chapters cover a wide range of topics, from basic introductions to pandas and data analysis, to more complex topics like boolean indexing of dataframes, categorical data, computational tools, creating DataFrames, cross sections of different axes with MultiIndex, data types, categorical variables, duplicated data, "gotchas" of pandas, graphs and visualizations, grouping data and time series data, holiday calendars, indexing and selecting data, IO for Google BigQuery, JSON, making pandas play nice with native Python datatypes, map values, and merge, join, and concatenate.

The text provides a comprehensive overview of the process of conducting experiments with a robot using the Robot Operating System (ROS) Navigation. The robot is given a starting and ending position within a room, and the distance and angle difference between these positions are measured. The robot's task is to reach the goal, which is published with these values. The robot's movements can be controlled by issuing a command, and the values can be adjusted to suit specific needs.

The text then presents two scenarios. In the first, the robot successfully reaches its goal by following a straight line and avoiding any obstacles in its path. It doesn't just avoid the obstacle, but also a region around it, known as the inflation radius. Upon reaching its goal, the robot rotates until it achieves the correct angle. In the second scenario, the robot's task is more challenging. It has to avoid several obstacles and reach a point that is beyond a corridor. Initially, the robot tries to avoid the obstacles by going around them, but upon encountering a wall, it decides to enter the inflation radius. Despite the high cost area, the robot successfully reaches its goal and adjusts itself to the correct direction.

The text concludes by discussing some details about the navigation. It mentions that the obstacles on the gmapping map and on the CostMaps should overlap each other perfectly, and that the inflation radius is usually avoided by the robot. It also notes that the global path is not perfectly followed by the local path in almost every situation, due to the different parameters used to calculate the smallest cost. The passage ends by stating that navigating through unknown environments is a challenging task, but the Navigation Stack tools have yielded great results, allowing the robot to create a dynamically generated map and achieve goals without crashing.

The text also discusses the development and application of the Learning Intelligent Distribution Agent (LIDA) Framework in the field of robotics. The LIDA Framework is a Java implementation of the LIDA conceptual model, a cognitive model of artificial consciousness. The authors present a tutorial on how to build a cognitive robotic system using the LIDA Framework and a new ROS module, the LIDA Bridge. The LIDA Bridge is designed to facilitate the development of a cognitive robotic system.

The text also discusses the recent advancements in the field of service robotics. Robots are now designed to operate in human circulation environments such as offices, hospitals, and museums, where interaction with people is necessary. These robots can perform tasks like delivery, cleaning, entertainment, and education. There is also the development of robotics towards accessibility like autonomous wheeled chairs. Another application that has been widely developed is the passengers transport by autonomous cars.

The text further discusses the concept of cognitive navigation, a field of research that associates the navigation problem with artificial intelligence, combining mobile robotics and cognitive processing of high-level perceptions of the environment. One widely used architecture for cognitive navigation uses a two-layer navigator, where the upper layer is responsible for identifying the high-level aspects (such as semantic interpretation of the sensor readings, and planning). An updated plan of action is then passed as input to the lower control layer, which then executes the plan.

The text discusses the development of a robot's head joints and an embedded system as part of a project. A mobile data capture platform was also created, which is essentially a bicycle trailer equipped with sensors similar to those on the actual robot. This platform was used to gather data for the design, training, and testing of new algorithms. The data was collected at a major European airport and was used to train the robot's perception components.

The text also explains the real-time people and group detection and tracking pipeline developed during the project. This pipeline starts with sensory data such as 2D laser scans, RGB-D point clouds, or stereo or monocular camera images. People are first detected using detectors specifically designed for the particular sensor modality. The detected people are then tracked, and the system attempts to maintain a consistent ID for each person for as long as possible.

The text further discusses the detection of people using RGB-D and 2D laser range data. While 2D laser range finders are relatively expensive, they offer data at high frequencies and cover a large field of view. However, they do not offer any appearance-based cues that can be used for people detection or re-identification. On the other hand, affordable RGB-D sensors are gaining popularity in many indoor close-range sensing scenarios. They do not require expensive disparity map calculations like stereo cameras and usually behave more robustly in low lighting conditions. The text also presents message definitions for person detection, which are intentionally kept as simple and generic as possible to allow reuse over a wide range of possible sensor modalities and detection methods.

The book provides a comprehensive guide to programming for robotics, focusing on the use of C++ and Python languages in the Ubuntu Linux environment. It begins by discussing the fundamentals of C++ programming, emphasizing its importance in working with the Robot Operating System (ROS). The book explains the C++ compiler in Ubuntu and the process of compiling a C++ file. It delves into the object-oriented concepts in C++, the differences between C++ classes and C structs, and key programming concepts like access modifiers and inheritance. It also covers file operations, namespaces, exception handling, and the Standard Template Library in C++. The chapter concludes with instructions on compiling C++ source code using Linux makefiles and CMakeLists.txt files.

The book then introduces Python programming in Ubuntu Linux, explaining that both C++ and Python are commonly used in robotics programming. The choice between the two depends on the preference for performance (C++) or ease of programming (Python). It discusses the trade-off between performance and development time when choosing a programming language for robotics applications. The book provides a brief history of Python, its design philosophy, and a timeline of its major milestones from inception in 1989 to the latest version released in 2016. It also provides instructions on how to start programming Python in Ubuntu Linux, how to check the Python executable path and version, and how to install Python manually. It concludes by providing a list of Python commands for two different versions of Python: 2.7.12 and 3.5.2.

The book then discusses the programming of robots using ROS. It explains how to install ROS on a Raspberry Pi, a small, affordable computer that can be used to learn programming. It covers the creation of a ROS workspace, the creation of a ROS package, and how to write ROS nodes using C++ and Python. It also discusses ROS launch files and how to include nodes in a launch file. The chapter concludes with a discussion on programming embedded boards such as the Arduino and the Raspberry Pi using ROS.

The next chapter focuses on creating wheeled robot hardware and software using ROS. The reader will learn how to make a low-cost, differential drive robot that is compatible with ROS. The chapter covers how to perform dead reckoning in the robot using ROS, how to assemble the robot hardware, interface sensors using Arduino, interface a ROS PC and a robot using a Bluetooth interface, create a robot model in ROS, and write nodes to move the robot and perform dead reckoning. The chapter concludes with a discussion on differential drive robot kinematics, including how to calculate the exact position and orientation of the robot from the wheel speed using a sensor called wheel encoders.

The book provides a detailed guide on how to use Ubuntu Linux for robotics, focusing on the installation of software applications and the use of command-line interface (CLI). It provides a cheat sheet of terminal commands useful for working with robots and ROS. Each command is explained with its usage and an example, and figures are included to illustrate the output or result of each command.

The book passage provides a comprehensive guide on the fundamentals of C++ and Python programming languages, their application in Ubuntu Linux, and their use in the Robot Operating System (ROS). The initial chapter delves into the basics of C++ programming, explaining the process of compiling a C++ file using the Ubuntu compiler. It further explores the object-oriented concepts in C++, highlighting the differences between C++ classes and structs in C, and important programming concepts like access modifiers and inheritance. The chapter also covers file operations, namespaces, exception handling, and the Standard Template Library in C++. It concludes by explaining how to compile C++ source code using Linux makefiles and CMakeLists.txt files.

The focus then shifts to Python programming in Ubuntu Linux. The book explains that C++ and Python are the common languages used in robotics programming, with the choice between the two depending on the preference for performance (C++) or ease of programming (Python). It discusses the trade-off between performance and development time when choosing a programming language for robotics applications. It provides a brief history of Python, highlighting its design philosophy, which emphasizes code readability and syntax, and its common use in robotics applications where less computation is required.

The book then provides a detailed guide on programming Python in Ubuntu Linux. It explains that Python interpreter is preinstalled in Ubuntu and provides a step-by-step guide on how to open the default Python version interpreter. It also provides a list of Python commands for two different versions of Python: 2.7.12 and 3.5.2. The chapter concludes by explaining how to install Python manually on Ubuntu 16.04 LTS and how to verify the Python installation by checking the Python executable path and version.

The book then discusses the programming of robots using the Robot Operating System (ROS). It begins by explaining how to install ROS on a Raspberry Pi, a small, affordable computer that can be used to learn programming. The chapter covers creating a ROS workspace, creating a ROS package, writing ROS nodes using C++ and Python, and programming embedded boards like the Arduino and Raspberry Pi using ROS. The chapter also includes examples of working with turtlesim in ROS and a Gazebo simulation of TurtleBot.

The next chapter introduces the creation of wheeled robot hardware and software using ROS. The reader will learn how to apply the concepts learned in the previous chapters to a real robot. This includes assembling the robot hardware, interfacing sensors using Arduino, interfacing a ROS PC and a robot using a Bluetooth interface, creating a robot model in ROS, and writing nodes to move the robot and perform dead reckoning.

The book then delves into the specifics of wheeled robots, explaining that they are a popular category of mobile robots that use wheels for locomotion. The most common and simple type of configuration used in wheeled robotics is the differential drive. The book explains that in this configuration, there are two active wheels that move the robot and one or more passive wheels to support the active wheels. The active wheels have actuation, but passive wheels do not. The book also explains the concept of differential drive robot kinematics, which involves calculating the exact position and orientation of the robot from the wheel speed using a sensor called wheel encoders. The position and orientation of a robot can be represented as (x,y,z) and (roll, pitch, and yaw). The book concludes by explaining that to analyze the motion of the robot, such as predicting the current position and orientation while the robot is moving, one must solve the robot’s kinematics equation.

The book provides a detailed guide on how to use Ubuntu Linux for robotics, focusing on the installation of software applications and the use of command-line interface (CLI). The Ubuntu Software, accessible through the Unity Launcher, is the direct way to install applications. However, for advanced tasks, the Ubuntu CLI, which is similar to the disk operating system (DOS) in Windows, is recommended. The CLI is faster and often used in system debugging. The Terminal tool, which can be found using the Ubuntu Dash search, is where the CLI is located. Knowledge of Linux terminal commands is essential for working with ROS (Robot Operating System).

The book then provides a cheat sheet of useful shell commands for working with robots and ROS. The 'man' command provides the manual page of a given command, 'ls' lists the content of files and folders in the current directory, 'cd' switches from one folder to another, 'pwd' returns the current path of the terminal, 'mkdir' creates an empty folder or directory, and 'rm' deletes a file. To delete a folder and its files, the 'rm -r' command is used, and to delete a file in the root file system, 'sudo rm' is used. The 'rmdir' command deletes an empty folder, but files may need to be deleted first.

The book continues with more commands. The 'mv' command moves a file from one location to another and renames it. The 'cp' command copies files from one location to another. The 'dmesg' command is useful for system debugging as it displays the kernel logs. The 'lspci' command lists the PCI devices in the PC, and the 'lsusb' command lists the USB devices in the system. Each command is accompanied by usage examples and figures to illustrate the output or result of the command.
